<div style=" text-align:center;">
<h1>DIWALI</h1>
</div>
<div style="text-align:center">
<img src="https://www.olyv.co.in/wp-content/uploads/Frame-11.png" alt="">
</div>

<div>
<p>
Diwali, also known as the Festival of Lights, is one of the most important and widely celebrated festivals in India. It usually falls in the months of October or November and is celebrated with great joy and enthusiasm by people of all religions, though it holds special significance for Hindus.

The festival marks the victory of good over evil and light over darkness. According to Hindu mythology, Diwali is celebrated to honor the return of Lord Rama to Ayodhya after fourteen years of exile and his victory over the demon king Ravana. People lit rows of lamps (diyas) to welcome him, and since then, the tradition of lighting lamps continues.

The celebrations of Diwali usually last for five days. Homes are cleaned and decorated with rangoli, flowers, and lights. Families perform Lakshmi Puja to seek blessings for wealth, prosperity, and happiness. Firecrackers, sweets, and gifts add more joy to the occasion. People wear new clothes, visit relatives, and share festive meals together.

Apart from its cultural importance, Diwali also teaches us valuable lessons. It reminds us that no matter how strong evil may seem, truth and goodness always win in the end. It also encourages unity, sharing, and spreading happiness among all.

In conclusion, Diwali is not just a festival of lights, but also a festival of hope, harmony, and new beginnings. It brings families and communities together, spreading love and positivity everywhere. 
 </p>
